   338→        <h2 id="History">History<span class="mw-editsection">[<a href="/wiki/Not-Wikipedia?action=edit&section=1">edit</a>]</span></h2>
   339→        <p>The origins of Not-Wikipedia can be traced back to early web design tutorials. Designers sought to replicate the clean, information-dense layout of Wikipedia's "Vector" skin. The term itself was coined to describe the phenomenon of "uncanny valley" web design, where a user believes they are browsing a wiki, only to realize the links do not function.</p>
   340→        <p>In 2026, the concept gained popularity as a method for testing <a href="/wiki/Large_language_model">Large Language Models</a> (LLMs) and their ability to generate structured HTML code.<sup><a href="#cite2">[2]</a></sup></p>
   341→
   342→        <h2 id="Characteristics">Characteristics<span class="mw-editsection">[<a href="/wiki/Not-Wikipedia?action=edit&section=2">edit</a>]</span></h2>
   343→        <p>Not-Wikipedia pages are defined by several distinct features:</p>
   344→        <ul>
   345→            <li><b>Visual Identity:</b> Use of the font families <i>Linux Libertine</i> for headings and <i>sans-serif</i> for body text.</li>
   346→            <li><b>Static Nature:</b> Unlike a real wiki, the "Edit" tab does not allow for actual content modification.</li>
   347→            <li><b>Color Palette:</b> Strict adherence to the hex codes <code>#f6f6f6</code> (background) and <code>#a7d7f9</code> (borders).</li>
   348→        </ul>
